kyudosha:

There are a number of dialectical differences between Received 
pronunciation (British English) and American English, just as there are 
dialectical differences across America.

No. 30 is used for the initial vowel sound in &quot;Andy.&quot;
No. 31 is used for what we called in school the &quot;long i&quot; sound.
No. 32 is similar to No. 34, but represents a longer vowel sound.  Think 
of a Brit dragging out the initial vowel as they say &quot;father&quot;.  If you 
pronounce &quot;father&quot; like &quot;bother,&quot; you probably don&#39;t need No. 32.
No. 34 is a shorter sound as in &quot;hot&quot; or &quot;cot.&quot;
I use No. 33 for the vowel sound in &quot;caught&quot; or &quot;awe&quot; although there is 
a vowel shift still underway in America which combines &quot;caught&quot; and 
&quot;cot&quot; so that they sound the same.  To those who still make the 
distinction, it sound very peculiar to hear someone speaking who does 
not make it.

Paige Gabhart

